nings":["English: habitational name from Ghent (<i>Gent</i> in Dutch), a city in Flanders, Belgium. Compare   Gent  ."]},{"name":"Gentes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Henri, Lucien, Marcel, Normand.","French (<b>Gentès</b>): probably a nickname derived from Old French <i>gent</i> ‘high born, noble’, also ‘nice, friendly’.","German: patronymic from the personal name   Gent  ."]},{"name":"Genther","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Otto.","German:","variant of   Gent  ."]},{"name":"Genthe","meanings":["German: variant of <b>Gente</b> (see   Gent  ), or a habitational name from Gentha in Saxony-Anhalt, east of Wittenberg."]}]},{"name":"Gertrude","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Germanic female personal name, derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>þrūþ</i> ‘strength’. The name is not found in England immediately after the Conquest, but only in the later Middle English period. It may have been introduced by migrants from the Low Countries who came to England in connection with the cloth trade, and was certainly in consistent use in some areas throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, although it was not generally popular until the 19th century, when many medieval names were revived. It has now fallen from favour again."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gertrude Gent was born before 1082, her father, Boudewijn de Gent, was 29 and her mother, Oda de Avegnes, was 55. She married Arnaud I d'Andres Viscount of Marchiennes. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1138, in Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Israel."},"et":{"Bef 1082–1138":"enne 1082–1138","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1059–1115":"1059–1115","1062–1097":"1062–1097","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1082–1138":"1082–1138","1115–1136":"1115–1136","1125–1148":"1125–1148","1053–1082":"1053–1082","1026–1082":"1026–1082","Aft 1136":"pärast 1136","1080":"10